eu.excitement.entailment.core.utilities.immutable

Interface ImmutableSet<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T -
    All Superinterfaces:
    ImmutableCollection<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.io.Serializable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ImmutableSetWrapper

    public interface ImmutableSet<T>
extends ImmutableCollection<T>
    Much like java.util.Set but only with "read" operations.

    Note: it is strongly recommended to use getImmutableSetCopy() method, in cases which an iterator runs on the and makes operations. I don't have the time to explain it now, but if you get runtime-exception when using for(X x : S) loops, or when using Iterator - try using a copy of the set instead of the original one. This is correct to java.util.Set as well, in which another mechanism (e.g. addAll() method) is used to create copies.

    Note: ImmutableSet may be non-thread-safe (depending on underlying implementation that may be non-thread-safe of read methods). (But usually ImmutableSets are thread safe, since even LinkedHashSet has no option to be ordered according to access, but according to insertion. See the JavaDoc for LinkedHashMap and LinkedHashSet in JDK documentation)

    Author:
    Asher Stern
